The transition committee chairman, Ikwuano local government council, Deacon Stanley Ojigbo has appointed 61 personal aides, saying that he would pay them stipends from his personal fund. Ojigbo announced this at a meeting with the appointees who are the coordinators and youth presidents of the four clans and 57 communities in the area in Isiala Oboro, the council headquarters. Congratulating them for the appointments, he urged them to remain law abiding and supportive of Governor Okezie Ikpeazu’s administration in the state, assuring that he will work for the welfare of the area. The chairman, who charged them to come up with proposals on how to raise the Internally Generated Revenue (IGR) of the area, stressed that they must represent their people well. He expressed joy that the area has remained peaceful and calm without any form of security breach, which he attributed to the synergy between the security agencies and the people. The onetime executive chairman of the council, sued for peace among the people especially now that the farming season is fast approaching. He, therefore urged those in authority and public spirited individuals and groups to use their position or wealth to carry the youth along to take them away from crime and criminal activities. Responding on behalf of his colleagues, the president, Ikwuano Youth Forum, Mr Santiago Agomuo thanked the chairman for the appointments, saying that Ojigbo’s love for the youth is unprecedented. He assured him that the youth are solidly behind his and Ikpeazu’s administrations, pledging that they would continue to work with both of them for the development of the area and the state.